pyang 1.7.3 does not appear to support the "invert-match" pattern modifier substatement as documented in YANG 1.1 RFC 7950 section 9.4.6 (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7950#section-9.4.6).

```
$ pyang --version
pyang 1.7.3

$ pyang -f yang --yang-canonical --lint ...etc..
<...filepath...>.yang:83: error: unexpected keyword "modifier"

# Example YANG code
    79        leaf leaf-name {
    80          type string {
    81            length "1..17";
    82            pattern "(all|none)" {
    83              modifier "invert-match";
    84            }
    85            pattern "[a-zA-Z~@%-_+:|\\[\\]]{1,17}";
    86          }
    87        }
```

Is this a known limitation?

In the Flask example app (but not the Flask ME one), the `done` route is defined like this
````python
@login_required
@app.route('/done/')
def done():
    return render_template('done.html')
````
In order for the `login_required` decorator to work, it must be "inside" of the `app.route` decorator. Currently the `done` route is accessible for non-authenticated users as well.

As of today inheritance is not intuitive:

```python
from autoclass import autoclass

@autoclass
class Foo:
    def __init__(self, foo):
        pass

@autoclass
class Bar(Foo):
    def __init__(self, bar):
        pass
```

yields
```bash
> ValueError: @autodict can not be set on classes that are already subclasses of Mapping, and therefore already behave like dict
```

In order for this to work, you have to use `@autoclass(autodict=False)` in the  parent class. But this is not user-friendly. The proposal would be to remove this exception, and make all dict implemented methods call the corresponding super() method where appropriate

Right now it takes a name, but could we do:

```
class C(HasTrait):

   foo = FooTrait():
   
   @observe(foo):
    def _(...):
         ...
```

and extract the name from the foo instance instead of requiring a string ? 

There is probably a reason **not** to do that, but just wondering why.

Hello everyone :)

I need to get some unit properties, but when I try to retrieve these values, I always obtain the default one.

```cpp
// [FBXImporter.cpp => InternReadFile function]

// take the raw parse-tree and convert it to a FBX DOM
Document doc(parser,settings);

// convert the FBX DOM to aiScene
ConvertToAssimpScene(pScene,doc);

auto globalSettings = doc.GlobalSettings();
auto unitScaleFactorTest = globalSettings.UnitScaleFactor();
auto originalUnitScaleFactorTest = globalSettings.OriginalUnitScaleFactor();
```

However, with the VS debugger, I can see that the value of these properties is not the default one and if I try to retrieve them like that, I get the proper values:

```cpp
auto globalSettings = doc.GlobalSettings();
auto unitScaleFactor = globalSettings.Props().Get("UnitScaleFactor")->As<TypedProperty<float>>()->Value();
auto originalUnitScaleFactor = globalSettings.Props().Get("OriginalUnitScaleFactor")->As<TypedProperty<float>>()->Value();
```

Please notice that I used _float_ type, and not _double_ as specified in the [FBXDocument.h](https://github.com/assimp/assimp/blob/master/code/FBXDocument.h#L1310) file. Beside, if I change the type in the macro call, it works like expected (calling the getters of global settings).

```cpp
fbx_simple_property(UnitScaleFactor, float, 1)
fbx_simple_property(OriginalUnitScaleFactor, float, 1)
```

Am I the only one with this problem?

