Hi,

My app uses Align to map the depth image to colour, so I have a 1:1 relationship between the colour image and aligned depth image. I've been playing with the post-processing filters and the problem I'm facing is that running the depth image through the filters reduces its dimensions so I no longer have the 1:1 mapping.
I've tried simply dividing the depth data index by the ratio between the size of the two images (colour and aligned depth which has been processed) like this:
```
var length = colourFrame.Width * colourFrame.Height;
var scale = length / (float)(depthFrame.Width * depthFrame.Height);

for(int idx = 0; idx < length; idx++)
{ 
    float distance = depthData[(int)(idx / scale)] * depthScale;
    uint colour = colourData[idx];
}
```
But this mapping doesn't work; I get a mess of depth values which don't correspond to the colour image. Is it possible to get align and post-processing working together like this?

Thanks,
James

Trying to migrate code to pybind11, I am facing the following code snippet, currently using boost.python
~~~C++
    const auto l = len(ucodes);
    for (auto i = 0; i < l; ++i)
    {
        using namespace boost::python;

        const object t = ucodes[i];
        extract<unsigned> num{t};
        if (num.check())
        {
            // ... Do something with num()
        }
        else
        {
            extract<tuple> er{t};
            if (!er.check())
            {
                PyErr_SetObject(PyExc_RuntimeError, t.ptr());
                return;
            }
            const auto range = er();
            // ... Do something with extract<unsigned>{range[0]}() and extract<unsigned>{range[1]}()
        }
    }
~~~
where `ucodes` is a function argument of type `const boost::python::list &`

According to [Docs » Python C++ interface » Python types](https://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/pycpp/object.html?highlight=cast_error), the best I can do is
~~~C++
    const auto l = len(ucodes);
    for (std::remove_cv_t<decltype(l)> i = 0; i < l; ++i)
    {
        const auto t = ucodes[i];
        try
        {
            auto num = py::cast<unsigned>(t);
            // ... Do something with num()
        }
        catch (const py::cast_error &) // this one
        {
            try
            {
                auto range = py::cast<py::tuple>(t);
                // ... Do something with py::cast<unsigned>(range[0]) and py::cast<unsigned>(range[1])
            }
            catch (const py::cast_error &e)
            {
                PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, e.what());
                return;
            }
        }
    }
~~~
Is there a way to not catch `py::cast_error`, particularly the first one?

## Issue description

Overload with default value of nullptr for a const char* seems to take low priority as if it requires a conversion.

## Reproducible example code

With the following code

    struct Foo;

    py::class_<Foo> (m, "Foo")
      .def (py::init (
        [] (const std::string &, const char *)
        {
          std::cout << "const char * constructor called" << std::endl;
          return Foo ();
        }),
        py::arg ("string"),
        py::arg ("const char *") = nullptr)
      .def (py::init (
        [] (const py::object &)
        {
          std::cout << "object constructor called" << std::endl;
          return Foo ();
        }));

According to the description of overload resolution in the docs, I was hoping that `Foo('hello')` would call the `const char *` constructor, but:

    >>> import mymodule
    >>> mymodule.Foo("hello")
    object constructor called
    <mymodule.Foo object at 0x7fb9c7110228>

    >>> mymodule.Foo("hello", None)
    const char * constructor called
    <mymodule.Foo object at 0x7fb9c7110298>

The constructor works when I pass None explicitly, but not when I leave it to the default value?

Thanks for this awesome library!

David

I believe this makes it a lot easier to write generic code using array_t

```diff
diff --git a/include/pybind11/numpy.h b/include/pybind11/numpy.h
index c224bd4..5795347 100644
--- a/include/pybind11/numpy.h
+++ b/include/pybind11/numpy.h
@@ -563,6 +563,7 @@ protected:
 
 template <typename T, int ExtraFlags = array::forcecast> class array_t : public array {
 public:
+    typedef T el_t;
     array_t() : array(0, static_cast<const T *>(nullptr)) {}
     array_t(handle h, borrowed_t) : array(h, borrowed) { }
     array_t(handle h, stolen_t) : array(h, stolen) { }
```

## Issue description

In Jupyter Notebook or in IPython I can normally press tab inside a function to autocomplete named arguments, but I cannot make this work for the example below. I can explicitly name the arguments, i.e. `add(first=2, second=3)` but not begin typing `sec...`+tab to complete to `second`. Is there a way of achieve this?

## Reproducible example code

```.cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
